            "title": "The world republic of letters",
            "abstract": "Principles of a world history of literature -- The invention of literature -- World literary space -- The fabric of the universal -- From internationalism to globalization -- The small literatures -- The assimilated -- The rebels -- The tragedy of translated men -- The Irish paradigm -- The revolutionaries \"The \"world of letters\" has always seemed a matter more of metaphor than of global reality. In this book, Pascale Casanova shows us the state of world literature behind the stylistic refinements - a world of letters relatively independent from economic and political realms, and in which language systems, aesthetic orders, and genres struggle for dominance. Rejecting facile talk of globalization, with its suggestion of a happy literary \"melting pot,\" Casanova exposes an emerging regime of inequality in the world of letters, where minor languages and literatures are subject to the invisible but implacable violence of their dominant counterparts.\" \"Inspired by the writings of Fernand Braudel and Pierre Bourdieu, this ambitious book develops the first systematic model for understanding the production, circulation, and valuing of literature worldwide. Casanova 's work provides a view of the political struggles of our modern world - one framed by sites of publication, circulation, translation, and efforts at literary annexation.\"--BOOK JACKET",
